The course " The Power of the Habsburgs: History, Culture and Art " combines history and art history. The course contextualizes the role of the Habsburgs as the leading dynasty of Europe during the end of the 15h century and the first half of the 16. century, concentrating on the role of personal relations, the court and the pieces of art exhibited at the court in the diplomatic relations of the Habsburg and in their performance of power. The Habsburg court can be considered an excellent example of European courtly culture of the time, where art and culture were harnessed into the service of the ideological program of the ruler.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course aims to give an overview of the political and diplomatic activities of the Habsburg monarchs form the end of the 15th century to the middle of the 16th century, with an emphasis on the role of their court, culture and art in its service.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student who has taken this course:  -	is familiar with the main characteristics of the politics of the Habsburg monarchs; -	will grasp the essence of the pre-modern political system, which was based on personal relations; -	acknowledges the connection between the political-diplomatic capabilities of a monarch and the splendor of his court; -	has gained elementary knowledge of culture at the Habsburg court, where luxury goods, often used for ideological aims, played an important role; -	is aware of the role artworks as political instruments.
